{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78eb8dd1-8346-464b-a4c3-919c16e38ada","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI `ContentPage` property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need platform-specific configuration for each OS:\n\n**iOS** — opt out of safe-area insets on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Android** — enable edge-to-edge drawing (required for pre-API 35; API 35+ does it by default). In your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window is not null)\n    {\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n        Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Image control** — make sure it fills and crops correctly:\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nAlso verify there's no `Padding` or `Margin` on the page or any parent layout wrapping your `Image`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22bfd667-7883-4a12-aeed-f1489a474000","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making an image go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but it's not working.\n\nThis is a .NET MAUI question about edge-to-edge/full-screen display. Let me think about what they need:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (especially targeting .NET 10), to achieve edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to:\n\n1. On **Android**: Starting with Android 15 (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default. \n\nFor earlier Android versions or to ensure consistent behavior, you'll need to configure the app to draw behind system bars, which might involve platform-specific settings in the Android project.\n\n2. On **iOS**: You need to handle safe area insets properly.\n\nThe issue is that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone won't make the image go behind the system bars—you likely need to set `IgnoreSafeArea` directly on the Image control itself, and potentially configure platform-specific properties to enable edge-to-edge rendering.\n\nIn .NET MAUI specifically, on iOS you'd use the platform-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to let content extend behind safe areas, and on Android you need to configure the window to be translucent and handle the status bar and navigation bar appropriately. The Image's `Aspect` property should also be set to something like `AspectFill` to fill the space correctly. I'm realizing that `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a standard property in .NET MAUI, so the user might be working with a custom implementation or misremembering the API. The real solution involves platform-specific configurations—on iOS using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` and on Android enabling edge-to-edge mode through MainActivity settings—plus ensuring the Image control itself isn't constrained by parent padding or margins.\n\nSetting up platform-specific window configuration...","outputTokens":1514,"requestId":"77F3:2D9C3A:185C4B:1CFFD8:69EAC0A7"},"id":"741f41d3-ffe2-4442-b07a-859588f30a38","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:00:53.978Z","parentId":"6dba6c2f-4bad-452a-9401-621112ab4f4e"}
